// di-snapsend — replicate immediately after an apt transaction.
//
// STAGE: DPkg::Post-Invoke (NOT Post-Invoke-Success). Verified on apt 3.0.x
// (Debian 13 / trixie): apt does NOT execute DPkg::Post-Invoke-Success for normal
// package operations (install/reinstall/remove all leave it unrun), so a hook placed
// there never fires. DPkg::Post-Invoke is the stage that runs reliably — it is the
// same stage snapper's own apt integration (80snapper / 81snapper-enhanced) uses.
//
// ORDERING: apt runs the entries within a single stage in filename sort order, so this
// file (95*) runs AFTER snapper's post-snapshot hook (80*/81*). By the time snapsend
// starts, snapper's post-snapshot — the consistent post-change @, including any
// kernel/grub/initramfs updates written by package postinst scripts — already exists.
// This pairs the live /boot + /boot/efi rsync tier with the matching snapshot, closing
// the timer's randomized-offset skew window for the case that matters (apt-driven
// OS/boot changes). The 95-vs-80/81 filename sort is therefore load-bearing: keep this
// file sorting after snapper's.
//
// SUCCESS GATING: Post-Invoke runs on every transaction, success or failure, and apt
// exposes no success signal to the hook — so unlike the original intent we do not gate
// on a clean transaction. This is benign: snapsend only mirrors already-committed
// snapshots + the live boot tier (it never propagates anything irreversibly, and the
// destination keeps history), snapper snapshots on this same stage regardless of
// outcome, and the hourly timer would replicate the identical state on its next tick
// anyway. Firing slightly more often than strictly necessary is the safe direction.
//
// --no-block: don't make apt wait for the (possibly minutes-long) btrfs send.
// start (not the script): reuse snapsend.service so the engine's flock, logging, and
//   resource limits apply. A collision with an in-flight run is a clean no-op (the engine
//   takes a non-blocking flock and exits via _AlreadyRunning).
// || true: a queued/failed service start must never fail the apt transaction.
DPkg::Post-Invoke { "if [ -x /usr/bin/systemctl ] || [ -x /bin/systemctl ]; then systemctl --no-block start snapsend.service || true; fi"; };
